1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,000
So here in week one, I want to talk about a great starting subject of how to set your mindset on how to think about your horse and about what they're thinking of.

2
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:23,000
So when you go in to your riding or your groundwork session with an intention, it goes way better.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:31,000
So I want you to listen to these, you know, preferably at the beginning and at the end of the week and give yourself almost like a little score.

4
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Did I get better with the thing that I'm trying to work on this week, number one?

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:41,000
And also, did I come with an intention every time I worked my horse?

6
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:47,000
So this week, I want you to think of putting yourself in your horse's shoes.

7
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:55,000
So I want you to think of what they could be thinking, just like you would another person.

8
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:04,000
So sometimes how I like to start with people and with horses is like, how is your day going?

9
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Can you ask your horse that question? Were they just turned out? Did they just come from a stall? What are the circumstances of their day? Did you just wake them up?

10
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Did they just eat? Did they not eat yet? They're so hungry.

11
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
All of those things matter when we go to work with our horse.

12
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:33,000
So, you know, another thing to think of that I hear a lot of people not really mentioning or giving themselves or giving their horses credit for is how are they feeling physically?

13
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Give your horse a chance to kind of answer that question and they answer in a couple ways.

14
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:49,000
They will answer when you palpate their body and they will give an answer like pinning their ears when you touch their shoulder or back or hip or wherever they're sore.

15
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Or they'll be super happy and when you hug them, they're like, yes, Nagomi, they're having a pretty good day.

16
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:59,000
Those things matter.

17
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,000
And then, of course, how does your horse feel about this exercise?

18
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
That's the biggest thing. Get very specific.

19
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:13,000
So in this, you know, in this week, you're going to go and be like, okay, well, are they confused?

20
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Are they sure? Do they feel safe? Are they distracted? Are they focused?

21
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:28,000
And why? And like, you know, what would the reason be that they are distracted or focused?

22
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:37,000
If they're very connected to you and they stay focused, even though there's chaos going around, then you can say, okay, well, we've just had a good connection.

23
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:46,000
But number one, you have to seek to understand before you can provide a solution or else your solution isn't going to be very good.

24
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Right. Like if you don't ever listen to your friend and they're complaining about something that they're really struggling with and they want to they want your help or they want your advice.

25
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:03,000
You just don't listen. How good is your advice going to be?

26
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:09,000
So let that ring in your ears there. You want to listen and have good advice.

27
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:17,000
So when your horse has a response or a reaction, ask yourself, do I understand why they had this reaction?

28
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Do I understand what the reaction was? Was the reaction to me? Was it the reaction to what they were thinking?

29
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Is this like an issue that doesn't, you know, have to do with me?

30
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Or were they reacting to their environment or something like this?

31
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,000
So if you can interact with horses, you can interact with people.

32
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And if you can interact with people, you can interact with horses.

33
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:48,000
And so ask yourself these questions before you provide a solution.

34
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:52,000
Lots of times people just want to jump on like, well, just stand still.

35
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:58,000
Well, what if he's reacting to something that requires him to not stand still like a bug?

36
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Right. Well, why don't you just why don't you just listen?

37
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Well, he doesn't know what he's listening for and why it's important to be listening to you.

38
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:12,000
What is the point of this? Right.

39
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And so I want you to put yourself in your horse's shoes.

40
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:25,000
I want you to write down every time, you know, you think you've got something new from your horse, like, oh, like I saw a different reaction.

41
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And I'm not even sure what the solution is, but my observing was better.

42
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000
So that's what I want you to bring to your call this week.

43
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
For the sake of the horse, let's get better.

